      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prayer as Tyranny</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Samuel P Del Propost letter on Aug 27 article scores movement toward 'unofficial' prayer at high school football games</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''South's Football Fans Still Stand Up and Pray'' (front page, Aug. 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''South's Football Fans Still Stand Up and Pray'' (front page, Aug. 27):</p>
        <p>The movement toward ''unofficial'' prayer at high school football games in response to the Supreme Court's decision against school-sanctioned, student-led prayer is the most compelling evidence so far that the court's decision was correct.</p>
        <p>Proponents of this aggressive effort to skirt the law are engaging in an egregious exercise of tyranny of the majority. One would expect such a movement in places like Kosovo or Bosnia rather than in the United States, which was founded on religious freedom for all.</p>
        <p>SAMUEL P. DEL PROPOST  Maplewood, N.J., Aug. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
